Image Classification: NASA Mars Image Library¶

The images used for this neural network application are taken from NASA's Open Data Portal.

https://data.nasa.gov/Space-Science/Mars-orbital-image-HiRISE-labeled-data-set-version/egmv-36wq

Mars orbital image (HiRISE) labeled data set version 3.2.0
(Citation: DOI: 10.5281/zenodo.4002935)

This dataset contains a total of 64,947 landmark images that were detected and extracted from HiRISE browse images, spanning 232 separate source images.

This set was formed from 10,815 original landmarks. Each original landmark was cropped to a square bounding box that included the full extent of the landmark plus a 30-pixel margin to the left, right, top, and bottom. Each landmark was then resized to 227x227 pixels. 9,022 of these images were then augmented to generate 6 additional landmarks using the following methods:

  1. 90 degrees clockwise rotation
  2. 180 degrees clockwise rotation
  3. 270 degrees clockwise rotation
  4. Horizontal flip
  5. Vertical flip
  6. Random brightness adjustment

The remaining 1,793 images were not augmented. Combining these with the 7*9,022 images, gives a total of 64,947 separate images.

We will follow the tutorial provided by Tensor Flow on Image Classification, and incorporate Nachiketa Hebbar's advice from his YouTube video, "Transfer Learning Using Keras(ResNet-50)| Complete Python Tutorial".

Normally, we should hit the site through code and download from the URL directly. This is a rather large dataset and it will require some manipulation. So, we download it directly, and we create the sub-directories as discussed in the tutorial.

Now, we try it - the download and ds creation directly. (There are some hiccups.)

import shutil

cwd = os.getcwd()
image_dir=os.path.join(cwd,"map-proj-v3_2")
print(image_dir)

fh_landmarks=open(os.path.join(image_dir,"landmarks_map-proj-v3_2_classmap.csv"))
dict_landmarks={}
for line in fh_landmarks:
    label, landmark = line.rstrip().split(",")
    print(label, landmark)
    dict_landmarks[label]=landmark.replace(" ","_")
print(dict_landmarks)
fh_landmarks.close()

fh_labels=open(os.path.join(image_dir,"labels-map-proj_v3_2_train_val_test.txt"))
dict_fileLabels={}
dict_fileSamples={}
for line in fh_labels:
    fname, label, sample = line.rstrip().split(" ")
    dict_fileLabels[fname]=label
    dict_fileSamples[fname]=sample
    if not os.path.exists(os.path.join(image_dir,dict_fileSamples[fname])):
        os.mkdir(os.path.join(image_dir,dict_fileSamples[fname]))
    if not os.path.exists(os.path.join(image_dir,dict_fileSamples[fname],dict_landmarks[label])):
        os.mkdir(os.path.join(image_dir,dict_fileSamples[fname],dict_landmarks[label]))
            
print(list(dict_fileLabels.items())[:9])
print(list(dict_fileSamples.items())[:9])
fh_labels.close()


move_count=0        
for f in os.listdir(image_dir):
    if f in dict_fileLabels.keys() and os.path.exists(os.path.join(image_dir,f)):

        sample = dict_fileSamples[f]
        label=dict_fileLabels[f]
        landmark=dict_landmarks[label]
        
        src_path=os.path.join(image_dir,f)
        dest_path=os.path.join(image_dir,sample,landmark,f)
        
        try:
            shutil.move(src_path,dest_path)
            move_count+=1
            print("Moved image".move_count)
        except FileNotFoundError:
            print("Could not find ", src_path)
            continue
        except:
            print("Other error occurred when attempting to access ", f)
            continue

3 - Load data using a Keras utility¶

Let's load these images off disk using the helpful tf.keras.utils.image_dataset_from_directory utility. This will take you from a directory of images on disk to a tf.data.Dataset in just a couple lines of code. If you like, you can also write your own data loading code from scratch by visiting the Load and preprocess images tutorial.

#Let's follow Nachiketa Hebbar's recipe for performing this work.
train_ds = tf.keras.preprocessing.image_dataset_from_directory(
    directory=train_data_dir,
    #subset="training",
    seed=123,
    label_mode="categorical",
    #color_mode="grayscale",
    image_size=(img_height,img_width),
    batch_size=batch_size
)

val_ds = tf.keras.preprocessing.image_dataset_from_directory(
    directory=val_data_dir,
    #subset="validation",
    seed=123,
    label_mode="categorical",
    #color_mode="grayscale",
    image_size=(img_height,img_width),
    batch_size=batch_size
)

test_ds = tf.keras.preprocessing.image_dataset_from_directory(
    directory=test_data_dir,

    label_mode="categorical",
    #color_mode="grayscale",

class_names = train_ds.class_names

4 - Fine-Tuning the ResNet50 Model¶

Here we bring in th eResNet50 model as an untrainable base-model, removing its last layer, and adding a couple of our own layers that we will train for our eight classes.

In [41]:
resnet_model = Sequential()

pretrained_model = ResNet50(include_top=False,
                            #pooling="avg", classes=len(class_names),
                            weights="imagenet")
for layer in pretrained_model.layers:
    layer.trainable=False
    
resnet_model.add(pretrained_model)
resnet_model.add(GlobalAveragePooling2D())
resnet_model.add(Dense(32, activation="relu")) #128, 256, 512, 1024 max'd out my laptop
resnet_model.add(Dense(len(class_names), activation="softmax"))

resnet_model.summary()

So, it appears that Loss increases for the validation sample as the number of epochs increase; yet, accuracy is fairly steady over the range. In fact, it seems that running for merely 4 epochs would have been a reasonable limit: validation accuracy is near its maximum over the range at 4 epaochs, and the loss function is only starting to climb at that that point.

5 - Performance Visualization¶

In [163]:
import pandas as pd
import seaborn as sn

#resnet_model = tf.keras.models.load_model("./ResNet50_MarsNN_w7.h5")
def produce_confusion_matix(strSampleName, strSampleDSname):
    cwd = os.getcwd()
    imageDir=os.path.join(cwd,"map-proj-v3_2",strSampleName.lower())
    os.listdir(imageDir)

    lst_subfolders=os.listdir(imageDir)     # must rebuild the landmarks dictionary, since the tf.data.Datasets use the 
    dict_subfolders={}                      # subfolder ordering in the project directory when estimating the model and 
    for i in range(len(lst_subfolders)):    # backpropagating.
        dict_subfolders[str(i)]=lst_subfolders[i]
    
    
    #Get predictions list
    predictions_sample=resnet_model.predict(strSampleDSname)

    pred_classnames_sample=[]
    pred_class_sample=np.argmax(predictions_sample,axis=1)
    for i in range(len(pred_class_sample)):
        pred_classnames_sample.append(dict_subfolders[str(pred_class_sample[i])])

    #Get actuals list
    elem_class_sample=[]
    for elem in strSampleDSname:
        elem_class_sample.append(elem[1])
    actual_classvectors_sample=np.concatenate(elem_class_sample, axis=0)
    actual_class_sample=np.argmax(actual_classvectors_sample,axis=1)

    actual_classnames_sample=[]
    for i in range(len(actual_class_sample)):
        actual_classnames_sample.append(dict_subfolders[str(actual_class_sample[i])])

    out_df = pd.DataFrame(np.vstack([pred_classnames_sample,actual_classnames_sample]).T,columns=["predicted_class","actual_class"])
    confusion_matrix = pd.crosstab(out_df["actual_class"], out_df["predicted_class"], rownames=["Actual"], colnames=["Predicted"])

    mdl_accuracy = (len(out_df[out_df["predicted_class"]==out_df["actual_class"]])/confusion_matrix.sum().sum()*100)
    
    sn.heatmap(confusion_matrix, cmap="Greens", annot=True, fmt="d")
    plt.title(strSampleName+" Sample Confusion Matrix")
    plt.show()
    print(strSampleName+" Sample Accuracy : {:0.2f}".format(mdl_accuracy))


produce_confusion_matix(strSampleName="Test", strSampleDSname=test_ds)
               

Test Sample Accuracy : 74.12

6 - Concluding Remarks¶

So, the confusion matrix demonstrates one f the difficulties we are having with this particular version of the model. The "other" class dominates everything. The fact that it "other" --> "other" mappng by the model is heavy allows for the high accuarcy value. We see that elsewhere (eliminating the "other" class) there is a fair amount of misclassification with the model.

We had to trim the information in our data elements from (227, 227) to (130, 130), in order not to overwhelm the hardware on whch this code was run. So, this may be an area that we could focus on to remediate the model.

Also, in our last version submitted in week 2, we used the functional form of neural network building, which did not overwhelm the hardware, even though we had just as many parameters and more in that model, and we used the full image renditions as our sample points. Thus, it seems that the Sequential methodology in TensorFlow has some overhead that the functional forms do not. Sequential forms are easire to understand and build (for the novice like me), but it comes at a cost.
